- canonical vocabulary is ambiguous
- constraints are not clearly prioritized

Do not invent missing information to fix these limitations.

## Downstream Use Instructions

When this projection is used by CreateRoadmapCompletionContext:

- Treat this projection as the desired strategic state.
- Treat completed epics as evidence of current strategic state.
- Do not let completed epic history redefine this projection.
- Compress completed epic history into realized capabilities, commitments, constraints, gaps, and drift signals.
- Preserve the canonical vocabulary in this projection.
- Mark evidence as insufficient when completed epic records do not support a claim.
- Do not infer codebase reality unless completed epic evidence includes implementation evidence.
- Do not select the next epic.
- Do not rewrite the roadmap.
- Do not modify this projection.

## Projection Integrity Checklist

Before finalizing, verify:

- The projection contains desired state only.
- No completed epic history is included.
- No implementation state is inferred.
- Every retained statement materially supports roadmap completion reasoning.
- Every major retained statement traces to the Project Context or is clearly marked projection-local.
- Canonical vocabulary is preserved.
- Excluded operational and implementation details are not present.
- The projection is compact enough to be passed into CreateRoadmapCompletionContext.
- The projection can serve as a stable reference frame for comparing completed epic evidence.
